for the individuals. But that does mean that sometimes you end up with things in contracts

472
00:29:39,463 --> 00:29:44,526
that don't necessarily apply to you. Things about, for example, you're making a single

473
00:29:44,526 --> 00:29:50,769
player game, but inside the contract it has things about multiplayer. You want to make

474
00:29:50,769 --> 00:29:57,193
sure that you get all of that shit out. Anything that's not appropriate to your game should

475
00:29:57,193 --> 00:30:00,755
not be in the contract. Because this just leads to problems in the future.

476
00:30:01,303 --> 00:30:09,430
Especially when you're rolling over or if you're bringing in new games from the IP, you need to make sure that the contract is your contract.

477
00:30:09,430 --> 00:30:11,372
There's nothing extra in there.

478
00:30:11,372 --> 00:30:14,494
Sorry, this is really boring. I am aware. I'm really sorry.

479
00:30:14,494 --> 00:30:18,278
And protect your rights, okay?

480
00:30:18,278 --> 00:30:24,223
You are the game developer, so you need to figure out what you want to keep.

481
00:30:24,223 --> 00:30:27,045
Many publishers will want your game's IP.

482
00:30:28,312 --> 00:30:30,194
or at least a percentage of your game's IP.

483
00:30:30,194 --> 00:30:35,058
So what this means is, if you make Super Mario the next one,

484
00:30:35,058 --> 00:30:39,041
it doesn't matter if you go with a different publisher for Super Mario 2,

485
00:30:39,041 --> 00:30:42,584
the original publisher still owns a percentage of it.

486
00:30:42,584 --> 00:30:47,147
So if you get a good deal, this isn't a bad thing.

487
00:30:47,147 --> 00:30:51,491
But if you get an okay deal, where you sign away your entire IP,

488
00:30:51,491 --> 00:30:52,111
holy shit!

489
00:30:53,450 --> 00:30:59,791
you know, that can be a really, really, really, really damaging, painful, painful thing.

490
00:30:59,791 --> 00:31:04,672
You also want to make sure who can organize bundles and who can organize discounts.

491
00:31:04,672 --> 00:31:13,393
Because there are thousands of horror stories out there of your game, it's a good game,

492
00:31:13,393 --> 00:31:17,414
sells for $10, but in the first month it doesn't sell enough copies.

493
00:31:17,414 --> 00:31:22,335
So your publisher panics and he starts selling your game for $1.

494
00:31:23,085 --> 00:31:28,309
So suddenly, instead of getting 70% of $9, you're getting 70% of $1.

495
00:31:28,309 --> 00:31:31,171
You're getting 70 cents per game, not including tax.

496
00:31:31,171 --> 00:31:37,415
It gets very low very, very quick. And this happens a lot.

497
00:31:37,415 --> 00:31:45,760
There are so many horror stories of publishers doing this, of publishers having the right...

498
00:31:46,149 --> 00:31:50,633
to just slash the value of a game and sell as many copies as possible as quickly as possible.

499
00:31:50,633 --> 00:31:56,977
Basically, dumping and running. You need to make sure that that doesn't happen,

500
00:31:56,977 --> 00:32:03,362
because that's not fun for anybody. Be realistic about your expectations within the contract.

501
00:32:03,362 --> 00:32:10,908
If you are expecting huge amounts of money, a large MG, be expecting to give things away.

502
00:32:11,834 --> 00:32:16,076
If you are not expecting that, then you should be

503
00:32:16,076 --> 00:32:19,578
haggling hard and making sure that you get the best deal possible.

504
00:32:19,578 --> 00:32:22,539
And the final one is

505
00:32:22,539 --> 00:32:27,301
get the contract checked by a lawyer. It's expensive.

506
00:32:27,301 --> 00:32:30,462
Lawyers aren't cheap and nobody likes them.

507
00:32:30,462 --> 00:32:35,625
But, understanding contracts is hard

508
00:32:35,625 --> 00:32:39,106
and it's really easy to make a mistake.

509
00:32:39,106 --> 00:32:40,967
I say this as someone who has made mistakes.

510
00:32:41,757 --> 00:32:44,257
So get a lawyer to check your contract.

511
00:32:44,257 --> 00:32:44,397
Okay?

512
00:32:44,397 --> 00:32:44,777
Okay?

513
00:32:44,777 --> 00:32:46,717
And take your time.

514
00:32:46,717 --> 00:32:53,539
When somebody presents you with a contract,

515
00:32:53,539 --> 00:32:55,659
you don't have to sign it that day.

516
00:32:55,659 --> 00:32:56,239
You should say,

517
00:32:56,239 --> 00:32:59,020
I need to take at least a week

